# Git commit best practices

## Sign off every commit (DCO)

**CRITICAL**: this repo's CI enforces the Developer Certificate of Origin — every commit in a PR must carry a `Signed-off-by:` trailer (see `.github/workflows/dco.yml`). Pass `-s` (or `--signoff`) on every `git commit`.

```bash
git commit -s -m 'fix(core): handle undefined expose on a service node'
```

Common pitfalls:

- `format.signoff=true` only affects `git format-patch`, not `git commit`. There is no `commit.signoff` option — the trailer must be added per commit.
- On `git commit --amend`, pass `-s` again so the trailer survives the amend.
- When rebasing to add sign-off across a range, only add it where missing — a blanket `git rebase --signoff` duplicates trailers on already-signed commits. Prefer an `--exec` that signs off only unsigned commits:

  ```bash
  git rebase <base> --exec \
    'git log -1 --format=%B | grep -qi "^Signed-off-by: " || git commit --amend --no-edit -s'
  ```

Verify before pushing — the last commit must show a sign-off:

```bash
git log -1 --format='%(trailers:key=Signed-off-by)'
```

## Stage explicitly

Prefer staging the specific files you changed over `git add -A` / `git add .`, which sweep in unrelated or untracked files (build artifacts, scratch files):

```bash
git add packages/makerkit-core/src/node.ts docs/design/10-domains/connection-contracts.md
git add -u   # modified tracked files only — never untracked
```

## Shell-safe commit messages

- Prefer **single quotes** around `-m` strings; avoid backticks (they can trigger command substitution). See [multiline-commit-messages](../../.claude/skills/multiline-commit-messages/SKILL.md) for multiline messages.

## A good commit

- One logical step — a coherent unit of change, reviewable on its own.
- Explains intent ("why"), not just mechanics ("what").
